This paper discusses the behavior of editors of a well-ranked journal and their potential use of coercive citations for personal benefit. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including digital libraries (cs.DL), cybernetics (cs.CY), cryptography and security (cs.CR), information retrieval (cs.IR), and social and information networks (cs.SI). However, since the paper focuses on the analysis of citation patterns, cs.DL and cs.IR are the most likely sub-categories, followed by cs.CR, cs.CY, and cs.SI.
